<h1>@HI{{kawari ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no <strong>kawari ni</strong>}}
<li> @Vplain{{}} @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

In these sentence patterns, <strong>@HI{{kawari ni}}</strong> indicates that something (including an action) replaces something else.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{before^life}}no <strong>kawari ni</strong> @KJ{{private}}ga @KJ{{teach}}emashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I taught in place of my teacher.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{soil^weekday^day}}ni @KJ{{attend^matter}}wo suru <strong>kawari ni</strong> @KJ{{month^weekday^day}}ha @KJ{{rest}}mimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    To make up for working on Saturdays I take Mondays off.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{me}}no @KT{{apa-to}}ha @KJ{{negative^convenience}}na<strong>kawari ni</strong> @KJ{{house^fare}}ga@KJ{{relax}}i.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    My apartment is inconvenient but the rent is cheap.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{sono@KJ{{car}}ha@KJ{{relax}}katta <strong>kawari ni</strong> yoku @KJ{{happenstance^hinder}}shita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    That car was cheap but it often broke down.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

In @N1{{}} <strong>@HI{{kawari ni}}</strong> @N2{{}}, @N2{{}} is replaced by @N1{{}} and in 
@S1{{}} @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}} @S2{{}}, @S2{{}} takes place to make up for the fact that @S1{{}} takes place.
<p></p>

In @S1{{}} @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}} @S2{{}}, @HI{{<strong>kawari ni</strong>}} can be replaced by @HI{{keredo(mo)}}, although the reverse does not always hold.
<p></p>

